context: By the time Oklahoma was admitted to the Union in <a0_0>1907<a0_0/>, Oklahoma City had surpassed <a1_0>Guthrie<a1_0/>, the territorial capital, as the population center and commercial hub of the new state. Oklahoma City was a major stop on <a2_0>Route 66<a2_0/> during the early part of the 20th century; it was prominently mentioned in <a3_0>Bobby Troup<a3_0/>'s 1946 jazz classic, "(Get Your Kicks on) Route 66", later made famous by artist <a4_0>Nat King Cole<a4_0/>.
